# Design — `<feature-name>`

> The technical plan that satisfies `requirements.md`. The implementer
> follows this without re-deciding anything; deviations require an
> updated design.md (and another human approval).

## Files touched

> Every file the implementation will create or modify. Reviewers compare
> the actual diff against this list; touching anything outside requires
> a justification in `progress/impl_<feature>.md`.

- `<path/to/file.go>` — `<one-line reason>`
- `<path/to/other.go>` — `<one-line reason>`

## Public API

> Function signatures, type definitions, route paths, CLI flag shapes —
> whatever counts as the interface for this feature. Show the actual
> Go/TypeScript/SQL/HTTP signature so the reviewer can grep for it.

```go
// <signature here>
```

## Algorithm

> Step-by-step pseudocode the implementer follows. Don't worry about
> language details — focus on the decisions: which order, which branches,
> which error paths.

1. `<step 1>`
2. `<step 2>`
3. `<step 3>`

## Error handling

> One row per failure mode. Tie each to an R-id from `requirements.md`
> (typically an IF/THEN / unwanted requirement).

| Condition | Response | Covers |
|---|---|---|
| `<error case 1>` | `<surface to caller>` | R4 |

## Alternatives considered

> 1-3 alternatives you discarded, each with a one-line justification.
> This is what makes a design review worthwhile: the reviewer sees what
> didn't work and can challenge the choice.

- **`<alternative A>`** — discarded because `<reason>`.
- **`<alternative B>`** — discarded because `<reason>`.

## Risks & open questions

> Anything you'd raise in a design-review meeting. The reviewer agent
> can refuse to approve if a high-impact risk has no mitigation plan.

- `<risk>` — mitigation: `<plan>`
- `<open question>` — to be answered by `<who/when>`
